#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:1
msgid "`loop`s can break with a value"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.19](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.19-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:5
msgid "`loop`s can now break with a value:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:8
msgid "// old code\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:15
msgid "// new code\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:20
msgid ""
"Rust has traditionally positioned itself as an “expression oriented "
"language”, that is, most things are expressions that evaluate to a value, "
"rather than statements. `loop` stuck out as strange in this way, as it was "
"previously a statement."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/control-flow/loops-can-break-with-a-value.md:25
msgid ""
"For now, this only applies to `loop`, and not things like `while` or `for`. "
"See the rationale for this decision in RFC issue [\\#1767](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rfcs/issues/1767)."
msgstr ""
